Note:
==============================================================================
IEEE 754-2008 binary32 (single precision) software implementation
==============================================================================

Format (32 bits):
  bit 31      : sign
  bits 30-23  : exponent (8 bits, bias 127)
  bits 22-0   : mantissa fraction (23 bits, implicit leading 1)

Special values:
  +0   : 0x00000000   -0  : 0x80000000
  +Inf : 0x7F800000   -Inf: 0xFF800000
  qNaN : exp=0xFF and mantissa MSB=1   (canonical 0x7FC00000)
  sNaN : exp=0xFF and mantissa MSB=0 with nonzero mantissa
  subnormal: exp=0, mantissa != 0 (no implicit leading 1)

References:
  IEEE 754-2008 (full standard)
  ucbtest / TestFloat vectors
  Hauser, John R., "Handling Floating-Point Exceptions in Numeric Programs"
  Goldberg, "What Every Computer Scientist Should Know About Floating-Point"

Storage:
  Float32 values are held in the bottom 32 bits of a Runa Integer (64-bit).
  The upper 32 bits MUST always be zero on the way out of every public
  operation; callers may rely on the bit pattern for pack/unpack.

Rounding modes (see ROUND_* constants):
  0 = round-to-nearest-even (IEEE 754 default)
  1 = round-toward-zero (truncation)
  2 = round-toward-positive-infinity
  3 = round-toward-negative-infinity
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/bitwise_core.runa" as Bits

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Format constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant F32_BITS as Integer is 32
Constant F32_EXP_BITS as Integer is 8
Constant F32_MANT_BITS as Integer is 23
Constant F32_BIAS as Integer is 127
Constant F32_EXP_MAX as Integer is 255

Note: 32-bit masks computed once
Constant F32_SIGN_MASK as Integer is 2147483648
Constant F32_EXP_MASK as Integer is 2139095040
Constant F32_MANT_MASK as Integer is 8388607
Constant F32_BIT32_MASK as Integer is 4294967295
Constant F32_MANT_HIDDEN as Integer is 8388608
Constant F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT as Integer is 4194304
Constant F32_CANONICAL_QNAN as Integer is 2143289344

Note: Common bit patterns
Constant F32_POS_ZERO as Integer is 0
Constant F32_NEG_ZERO as Integer is 2147483648
Constant F32_POS_INF as Integer is 2139095040
Constant F32_NEG_INF as Integer is 4286578688
Constant F32_POS_ONE as Integer is 1065353216

Note: Rounding modes shared across the binary family.
Constant ROUND_NEAREST_EVEN as Integer is 0
Constant ROUND_TOWARD_ZERO as Integer is 1
Constant ROUND_TOWARD_POSITIVE as Integer is 2
Constant ROUND_TOWARD_NEGATIVE as Integer is 3

Note: Exception flags (mirrors IEEE 754 § 7).
Constant FLAG_INVALID as Integer is 1
Constant FLAG_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO as Integer is 2
Constant FLAG_OVERFLOW as Integer is 4
Constant FLAG_UNDERFLOW as Integer is 8
Constant FLAG_INEXACT as Integer is 16

Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: Module-local state. Rounding mode and exception flags are global because
Note: IEEE 754 defines them as part of the executing thread's environment.
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Let F32_ROUNDING_MODE be 0
Let F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bit-pattern helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_mask32" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Truncate value to 32 bits so the upper half of the Runa Integer is zero.
    Used at every boundary that produces or accepts a Float32 bit pattern.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Logical-AND with 0xFFFFFFFF. The compiler lowers this to a single andq
    on x86-64 / and on aarch64, riscv, mips, powerpc.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Inlinable; cost is one ALU op. Kept as a proc to make intent explicit.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function over Integer; no memory access, no side effects.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return value bitwise and F32_BIT32_MASK
End Process

Process called "f32_get_sign" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the sign bit (0 or 1) from a 32-bit IEEE 754 single value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Shift right by 31, mask with 1 so the result is always 0 or 1 even
    when the input has stray upper-half bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops on every backend.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure; safe for use on attacker-controlled bit patterns.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let shifted be bits shifted right by 31
    Return shifted bitwise and 1
End Process

Process called "f32_get_exponent" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the biased 8-bit exponent field from a Float32 bit pattern.
    Returns an integer in [0, 255]. The bias is NOT removed.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Shift right by 23 then mask with 0xFF.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, two ALU ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let shifted be bits shifted right by F32_MANT_BITS
    Return shifted bitwise and 255
End Process

Process called "f32_get_mantissa" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the 23-bit mantissa fraction (no hidden bit) from a Float32.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    AND with the mantissa mask.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One ALU op.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return bits bitwise and F32_MANT_MASK
End Process

Process called "f32_pack" takes sign as Integer, biased_exp as Integer, mantissa as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Combine the three IEEE 754 fields into a single 32-bit bit pattern.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Mask each field to its width, shift into place, OR together, then mask
    the 32-bit result so callers cannot see stray upper-half bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six ALU ops total; produces no branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Defensive masking guards against caller passing wider values.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let s_field be sign bitwise and 1
    Let e_field be biased_exp bitwise and 255
    Let m_field be mantissa bitwise and F32_MANT_MASK
    Let s_shift be s_field shifted left by 31
    Let e_shift be e_field shifted left by F32_MANT_BITS
    Let combined be s_shift bitwise or e_shift
    Set combined to combined bitwise or m_field
    Return proc f32_mask32 with combined
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Classification predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_is_zero" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A Float32 is zero iff every bit except the sign bit is zero.
    +0 and -0 both qualify. Per IEEE 754 § 5.11, they compare equal but
    have distinct bit patterns.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Strip the sign and compare against 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops + one branch worth.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let payload be bits bitwise and 2147483647
    If payload is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_is_inf" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Infinity has exponent=0xFF and mantissa=0. Sign bit distinguishes
    +Inf from -Inf.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Strip sign, compare against the +Inf bit pattern.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops + branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let payload be bits bitwise and 2147483647
    If payload is equal to F32_POS_INF:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_is_nan" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A NaN has exp=0xFF and mantissa != 0. Per IEEE 754 § 6.2 quiet vs.
    signaling distinction is in the mantissa MSB; both forms are NaN.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Extract exponent and mantissa; the value is NaN exactly when
    exponent is 0xFF AND mantissa is nonzero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two field extracts and two branches; fully constant-time on
    register-renaming architectures.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with bits
    If exp is not equal to F32_EXP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with bits
    If mant is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_is_signaling_nan" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    sNaN: exp=0xFF, mantissa nonzero, and the MSB of the mantissa is 0.
    Per IEEE 754-2008 § 6.2.1 ("MSB=0 is signaling, MSB=1 is quiet").
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reject non-NaN first, then inspect bit 22 of the mantissa.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three ALU ops + one branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let nan be proc f32_is_nan with bits
    If nan is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with bits
    Let msb be mant bitwise and F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT
    If msb is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_is_subnormal" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Subnormal numbers have biased exponent 0 and nonzero mantissa.
    They represent values smaller than 2^-126 with reduced precision.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reject when exponent != 0 or mantissa == 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two field reads + two branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with bits
    If exp is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with bits
    If mant is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_is_normal" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Normal numbers have 0 < biased exponent < 0xFF. Subnormals, zero,
    infinities, and NaNs are all rejected.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Range check on the biased exponent field.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two field reads + two branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with bits
    If exp is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If exp is equal to F32_EXP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_is_finite" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A finite Float32 is anything that is not Inf and not NaN. Per
    IEEE 754 § 2.1.39, finite includes zero, subnormals, and normals.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reject only the exp=0xFF case.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One field read + one branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with bits
    If exp is equal to F32_EXP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_is_negative" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the sign bit is set, 0 otherwise. Does NOT exclude
    -0 or -NaN: the sign bit is the only criterion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Read the sign bit.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc f32_get_sign with bits
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Rounding-mode and exception-flag accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_set_rounding_mode" takes mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Switch the active rounding mode for subsequent Float32 ops. Modes
    outside [0,3] are ignored to keep the FPU state well-defined.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Range-check and store.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Affects module-global state; callers that interleave ops on
    different threads must serialize externally.
    @End Security_Scope
    If mode is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mode is greater than 3:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set F32_ROUNDING_MODE to mode
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_get_rounding_mode" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Read the active rounding mode.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single memory load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read-only access.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return F32_ROUNDING_MODE
End Process

Process called "f32_raise_flag" takes flag as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    OR a flag into the exception register without clearing existing
    flags. IEEE 754 § 7.2 requires sticky behavior until explicitly
    cleared.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Bitwise OR.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load + OR + store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Module-global mutation; serialize externally for multi-thread use.
    @End Security_Scope
    Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or flag
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_clear_flags" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reset the sticky exception register to zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single store.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Module-global mutation.
    @End Security_Scope
    Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_get_flags" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Snapshot of the sticky exception register.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read-only.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Unary operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_neg" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per IEEE 754 § 5.5.1, negation flips the sign bit even on NaN and Inf.
    -0 becomes +0 and vice versa.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    XOR with the sign mask, mask to 32 bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let flipped be bits bitwise xor F32_SIGN_MASK
    Return proc f32_mask32 with flipped
End Process

Process called "f32_abs" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per IEEE 754 § 5.5.1, abs clears the sign bit. NaN payloads survive.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    AND with the mask that has the sign bit zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ALU ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cleared be bits bitwise and 2147483647
    Return proc f32_mask32 with cleared
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comparison predicates (NaN-aware)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way IEEE 754 comparison. Returns -1 if a<b, 0 if a==b, 1 if a>b,
    and 2 for unordered (either operand is NaN, per IEEE 754 § 5.11).
    Distinguishes -0 from +0 only via sign; numerically they are equal.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    NaN check first. Then handle sign agreement:
      - same sign: compare bit patterns directly (with sign flip on negatives
        because a more-negative number has a larger magnitude bit pattern).
      - different signs: positive is greater unless both are zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    A few branches; the hot path is two field reads and one compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure; no global mutation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b
    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Return 2
    End If
    If b_nan is equal to 1:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Equal bit-patterns short-circuit (catches +0==+0, -0==-0, etc.)
    If a is equal to b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sign_a be proc f32_get_sign with a
    Let sign_b be proc f32_get_sign with b

    Note: +0 == -0 special case
    Let a_is_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a
    Let b_is_zero be proc f32_is_zero with b
    If a_is_zero is equal to 1:
        If b_is_zero is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let mag_a be a bitwise and 2147483647
    Let mag_b be b bitwise and 2147483647

    If sign_a is equal to sign_b:
        If sign_a is equal to 0:
            If mag_a is less than mag_b:
                Return -1
            End If
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: both negative: larger magnitude bits => smaller value
        If mag_a is less than mag_b:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: differing signs and neither is zero => the negative is smaller
    If sign_a is equal to 1:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_eq" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 ==: false whenever either operand is NaN, including NaN==NaN.
    +0 == -0 holds.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Delegate to f32_compare and check for the 0 (ordered-equal) verdict.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_ne" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 !=: true whenever the operands are unordered or numerically
    distinct. Specifically, NaN != anything (including itself) is true.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Complement of f32_eq.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_lt" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 <: false if unordered.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    f32_compare verdict of -1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to -1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_le" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 <=: false if unordered.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    f32_compare verdict of -1 or 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to -1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_gt" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 >: false if unordered.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    f32_compare verdict of 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_ge" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 >=: false if unordered.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    f32_compare verdict of 0 or 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by f32_compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be proc f32_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If c is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Special-result constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_make_qnan" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the canonical quiet NaN. Used when invalid ops must yield NaN.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Return the constant 0x7FC00000.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
End Process

Process called "f32_make_inf" takes sign as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct ±Inf without invoking the rounding machinery.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Build via f32_pack with exp=0xFF and mantissa=0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Composes one ALU chain.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If sign is equal to 0:
        Return F32_POS_INF
    End If
    Return F32_NEG_INF
End Process

Process called "f32_make_zero" takes sign as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct ±0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sign bit only.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If sign is equal to 0:
        Return F32_POS_ZERO
    End If
    Return F32_NEG_ZERO
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal: mantissa rounding using guard/round/sticky
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_round_grs" takes sign as Integer, mant as Integer, guard as Integer, round as Integer, sticky as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Apply the active rounding mode to a 24-bit mantissa (hidden bit
    included) extended with one guard bit, one round bit, and one sticky
    bit. Returns 0 if no increment is needed, 1 if the mantissa should
    be incremented by 1 ULP. Caller is responsible for handling the
    "mantissa overflow into the next binade" case after the increment.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Round-to-nearest-even (mode 0): increment if guard=1 AND (round=1
    OR sticky=1 OR mantissa LSB=1). All ties to even.
    Round-toward-zero (mode 1): never increment.
    Round-toward-positive (mode 2): increment for positive numbers when
    any extra bit is set.
    Round-toward-negative (mode 3): increment for negative numbers when
    any extra bit is set.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Branch-heavy but constant-time per mode.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure; reads module rounding mode.
    @End Security_Scope

    If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_NEAREST_EVEN:
        If guard is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        If round is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        If sticky is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: exact half - round to even
        Let lsb be mant bitwise and 1
        If lsb is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_ZERO:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let extra be guard bitwise or round
    Set extra to extra bitwise or sticky

    If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_POSITIVE:
        If sign is equal to 0:
            If extra is not equal to 0:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_NEGATIVE:
        If sign is equal to 1:
            If extra is not equal to 0:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: Internal: assemble a Float32 from sign + signed unbiased exponent +
Note: an extended 27-bit mantissa carrying GRS bits. The mantissa layout is
Note:    bit 26: hidden bit (1 for normals, 0 for subnormal results)
Note:    bits 25..3: 23-bit fraction
Note:    bit 2: guard
Note:    bit 1: round
Note:    bit 0: sticky
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Process called "f32_finalize" takes sign as Integer, unbiased_exp as Integer, ext_mant as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Normalize, round, handle exponent overflow/underflow, and pack into a
    32-bit Float32. This is the post-arithmetic rounding step shared by
    add/sub/mul/div/sqrt.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Steps:
      1. Normalize: shift the extended mantissa left until bit 26 is set
         (preserve sticky bit by ORing into bit 0 during right shifts).
         If bit > 26, shift right and OR shifted-out bits into sticky.
      2. Compute biased exponent. Detect underflow (biased < 1) and
         denormalize by right-shifting (with sticky accumulation).
      3. Extract guard/round/sticky from the bottom three bits.
      4. Strip GRS bits.
      5. Apply f32_round_grs and increment if needed; if the increment
         carries out of bit 23 (mantissa overflow), shift right and bump
         the exponent.
      6. Detect overflow (biased >= 0xFF): return signed Inf or the
         largest finite (depending on rounding mode), set the OVERFLOW
         and INEXACT flags.
      7. Detect underflow to zero: return signed zero, set UNDERFLOW
         and INEXACT (if any of guard/round/sticky was set).
      8. Pack normal/subnormal result.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case ~30 ALU ops with a small bounded loop for normalization.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Internal; callers supply trusted intermediate values.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mant be ext_mant
    Let exp be unbiased_exp

    If mant is equal to 0:
        Return proc f32_make_zero with sign
    End If

    Note: --- Right-normalize if mantissa has bits above position 26 ---
    Let upper be mant shifted right by 27
    While upper is not equal to 0:
        Let lost_bit be mant bitwise and 1
        Set mant to mant shifted right by 1
        Set mant to mant bitwise or lost_bit
        Set exp to exp plus 1
        Set upper to mant shifted right by 27
    End While

    Note: --- Left-normalize if bit 26 is not set ---
    Let bit26_mask be 67108864
    Let top be mant bitwise and bit26_mask
    While top is equal to 0:
        If mant is equal to 0:
            Return proc f32_make_zero with sign
        End If
        Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
        Set exp to exp minus 1
        Set top to mant bitwise and bit26_mask
    End While

    Note: --- Apply bias ---
    Let biased be exp plus F32_BIAS

    Note: --- Subnormal: shift right until biased reaches 1 ---
    If biased is less than 1:
        Let shift_amount be 1 minus biased
        Set biased to 0
        Note: shift right shift_amount bits, accumulating sticky
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than shift_amount:
            Let lost be mant bitwise and 1
            Set mant to mant shifted right by 1
            Set mant to mant bitwise or lost
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: --- Extract GRS ---
    Let sticky be mant bitwise and 1
    Let round_bit be (mant shifted right by 1) bitwise and 1
    Let guard be (mant shifted right by 2) bitwise and 1
    Let mant_only be mant shifted right by 3

    Let inexact be guard bitwise or round_bit
    Set inexact to inexact bitwise or sticky

    Let increment be proc f32_round_grs with sign, mant_only, guard, round_bit, sticky
    If increment is equal to 1:
        Set mant_only to mant_only plus 1
    End If

    Note: --- Mantissa overflow after rounding (e.g., 1.111... + ulp -> 10.000...) ---
    Let overflow_mask be 16777216
    If (mant_only bitwise and overflow_mask) is not equal to 0:
        Set mant_only to mant_only shifted right by 1
        Set biased to biased plus 1
    End If

    Note: --- Subnormal-to-normal promotion after rounding ---
    If biased is equal to 0:
        If (mant_only bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is not equal to 0:
            Set biased to 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: --- Overflow to Inf / largest finite ---
    If biased is greater than or equal to F32_EXP_MAX:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_OVERFLOW
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INEXACT
        If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_ZERO:
            Note: Largest finite magnitude
            Return proc f32_pack with sign, 254, F32_MANT_MASK
        End If
        If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_POSITIVE:
            If sign is equal to 1:
                Return proc f32_pack with sign, 254, F32_MANT_MASK
            End If
            Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
        End If
        If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_NEGATIVE:
            If sign is equal to 0:
                Return proc f32_pack with sign, 254, F32_MANT_MASK
            End If
            Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
        End If
        Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
    End If

    Note: --- Underflow to zero ---
    If biased is equal to 0:
        If mant_only is equal to 0:
            If inexact is not equal to 0:
                Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_UNDERFLOW
                Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INEXACT
            End If
            Return proc f32_make_zero with sign
        End If
        Note: subnormal result with hidden bit cleared
        If inexact is not equal to 0:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_UNDERFLOW
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INEXACT
        End If
        Let m_field_sub be mant_only bitwise and F32_MANT_MASK
        Return proc f32_pack with sign, 0, m_field_sub
    End If

    If inexact is not equal to 0:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INEXACT
    End If

    Note: --- Normal result ---
    Let final_mant be mant_only bitwise and F32_MANT_MASK
    Return proc f32_pack with sign, biased, final_mant
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Addition / subtraction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_propagate_nan" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per IEEE 754 § 6.2.3, when one or more operands are NaN, the result
    must be a NaN. Prefer the first NaN operand and quiet it.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Inspect both operands. Convert signaling NaN to quiet by setting
    the MSB of the mantissa. Set INVALID flag if any sNaN was seen.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three branches in the common case.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Module-global flag mutation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b
    If a_nan is equal to 0:
        If b_nan is equal to 0:
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
    End If

    Let a_snan be proc f32_is_signaling_nan with a
    Let b_snan be proc f32_is_signaling_nan with b
    If a_snan is equal to 1:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
    End If
    If b_snan is equal to 1:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
    End If

    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Let payload_a be a bitwise or F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT
        Return proc f32_mask32 with payload_a
    End If
    Let payload_b be b bitwise or F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT
    Return proc f32_mask32 with payload_b
End Process

Process called "f32_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 binary32 addition with correct rounding and special-value
    semantics: NaN propagation, Inf+Inf = Inf, Inf - Inf = NaN, +0 + -0 = +0
    (round-nearest), etc. Per IEEE 754 § 5.4.1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation.
    2. Inf handling (Inf + Inf, Inf - Inf, Inf + finite).
    3. Zero handling (0 + 0 preserves -0 only when both are -0 under
       round-nearest; under round-toward-negative, +0 + -0 = -0).
    4. Extract sign/exp/mant for both operands. Add the hidden bit.
    5. Align the smaller exponent up to the larger by right-shifting its
       mantissa, accumulating shifted-out bits into a sticky bit.
    6. If signs match, add mantissas. If they differ, subtract the smaller
       magnitude from the larger and the result sign is the larger's sign.
    7. Shift the mantissa left by 3 to reserve guard/round/sticky slots,
       then hand to f32_finalize for normalization, rounding, packing.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Branch-heavy in the special-case prologue; the hot path runs in
    constant time on dispatch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates the module exception flag register.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with a
    Let b32 be proc f32_mask32 with b

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b32
    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If
    If b_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If

    Let a_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    Let b_inf be proc f32_is_inf with b32
    Let sign_a be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let sign_b be proc f32_get_sign with b32

    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If b_inf is equal to 1:
            If sign_a is equal to sign_b:
                Return proc f32_make_inf with sign_a
            End If
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        Return a32
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        Return b32
    End If

    Let a_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    Let b_zero be proc f32_is_zero with b32
    If a_zero is equal to 1:
        If b_zero is equal to 1:
            If sign_a is equal to sign_b:
                Return a32
            End If
            Note: +0 + -0: result sign is + except for round-toward-negative
            If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_NEGATIVE:
                Return F32_NEG_ZERO
            End If
            Return F32_POS_ZERO
        End If
        Return b32
    End If
    If b_zero is equal to 1:
        Return a32
    End If

    Note: --- Extract fields ---
    Let exp_a be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let exp_b be proc f32_get_exponent with b32
    Let mant_a be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32
    Let mant_b be proc f32_get_mantissa with b32

    Note: Add hidden bit for normals; subnormals already have correct mantissa
    Let true_exp_a be exp_a
    Let true_exp_b be exp_b
    If exp_a is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_a to 1
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_a to mant_a bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If
    If exp_b is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_b to 1
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_b to mant_b bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If

    Note: Make mantissas extended: shift left by 3 to reserve GRS
    Set mant_a to mant_a shifted left by 3
    Set mant_b to mant_b shifted left by 3

    Note: --- Align exponents: shift smaller mantissa right with sticky ---
    Let aligned_exp be true_exp_a
    If true_exp_a is less than true_exp_b:
        Let diff_a be true_exp_b minus true_exp_a
        Note: cap shift at 32 to avoid losing all info beyond what sticky tracks
        If diff_a is greater than 32:
            Set diff_a to 32
        End If
        Let i_a be 0
        While i_a is less than diff_a:
            Let lost_a be mant_a bitwise and 1
            Set mant_a to mant_a shifted right by 1
            Set mant_a to mant_a bitwise or lost_a
            Set i_a to i_a plus 1
        End While
        Set aligned_exp to true_exp_b
    End If
    If true_exp_b is less than true_exp_a:
        Let diff_b be true_exp_a minus true_exp_b
        If diff_b is greater than 32:
            Set diff_b to 32
        End If
        Let i_b be 0
        While i_b is less than diff_b:
            Let lost_b be mant_b bitwise and 1
            Set mant_b to mant_b shifted right by 1
            Set mant_b to mant_b bitwise or lost_b
            Set i_b to i_b plus 1
        End While
        Set aligned_exp to true_exp_a
    End If

    Note: --- Combine ---
    Let result_sign be sign_a
    Let result_mant be 0
    If sign_a is equal to sign_b:
        Set result_mant to mant_a plus mant_b
    Otherwise:
        Note: Effective subtraction: compute |a| - |b| with correct sign
        If mant_a is greater than or equal to mant_b:
            Set result_mant to mant_a minus mant_b
            Set result_sign to sign_a
        Otherwise:
            Set result_mant to mant_b minus mant_a
            Set result_sign to sign_b
        End If
    End If

    If result_mant is equal to 0:
        Note: True zero from cancellation; sign is + under round-nearest,
        Note: but - under round-toward-negative.
        If F32_ROUNDING_MODE is equal to ROUND_TOWARD_NEGATIVE:
            Return F32_NEG_ZERO
        End If
        Return F32_POS_ZERO
    End If

    Note: f32_finalize expects bit 26 = hidden bit and bits 2/1/0 = G/R/S.
    Note: The mantissa here lives at bit (23+3)=26 if no carry; if carry from
    Note: same-sign addition, bit 27 is set, which f32_finalize handles by
    Note: right-normalizing.
    Let unbiased be aligned_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Return proc f32_finalize with result_sign, unbiased, result_mant
End Process

Process called "f32_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    a - b = a + (-b). Sign flip on b is bit-level; even NaN -b gives a NaN
    with flipped sign per IEEE 754 § 5.5.1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Negate b and delegate to f32_add.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One extra XOR and add cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Inherits mutation behavior from f32_add.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let neg_b be proc f32_neg with b
    Return proc f32_add with a, neg_b
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Multiplication
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 binary32 multiplication with correct rounding. Result sign is
    the XOR of the input signs. Special values per IEEE 754 § 6.1:
      Inf * 0 = NaN (invalid)
      Inf * finite = Inf
      0 * 0 = 0
      NaN * anything = NaN
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. NaN / Inf / zero special-case dispatch.
    2. Extract sign/exp/mant. Add hidden bit for normals; for subnormals,
       normalize the mantissa (left-shift until bit 23 set) and adjust
       the unbiased exponent accordingly.
    3. Multiply mantissas as 24-bit unsigned numbers, giving a 48-bit
       product. Multi-limb is not required because both fit in Runa's
       63-bit signed Integer.
    4. Add exponents (unbiased), shift product into the f32_finalize
       extended-mantissa layout, hand to f32_finalize.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Mantissa multiplication is a single Integer multiply; finalization
    handles normalization in a bounded loop.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with a
    Let b32 be proc f32_mask32 with b

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b32
    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If
    If b_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If

    Let sign_a be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let sign_b be proc f32_get_sign with b32
    Let result_sign be sign_a bitwise xor sign_b

    Let a_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    Let b_inf be proc f32_is_inf with b32
    Let a_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    Let b_zero be proc f32_is_zero with b32

    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If b_zero is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        Return proc f32_make_inf with result_sign
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        If a_zero is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        Return proc f32_make_inf with result_sign
    End If

    If a_zero is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_make_zero with result_sign
    End If
    If b_zero is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_make_zero with result_sign
    End If

    Let exp_a be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let exp_b be proc f32_get_exponent with b32
    Let mant_a be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32
    Let mant_b be proc f32_get_mantissa with b32

    Let true_exp_a be exp_a
    Let true_exp_b be exp_b
    If exp_a is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_a to 1
        Note: Normalize subnormal: shift until bit 23 set
        While (mant_a bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant_a to mant_a shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp_a to true_exp_a minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_a to mant_a bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If
    If exp_b is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_b to 1
        While (mant_b bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant_b to mant_b shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp_b to true_exp_b minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_b to mant_b bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If

    Note: 24-bit x 24-bit -> 48-bit product. Bits 47..0.
    Let product be mant_a multiplied by mant_b

    Note: --- Place product into the f32_finalize extended-mantissa layout:
    Note:    bit 26 should hold the hidden bit. The 24-bit mantissas have
    Note:    their hidden bit at position 23, so the product sits at bit 46
    Note:    or 47 (depending on whether the leading bits multiplied to 1.x
    Note:    or 1.x*2). f32_finalize handles right-normalization, so we just
    Note:    need to shift the product down so that the lowest-position
    Note:    representation has the hidden bit somewhere in [26, 27] and the
    Note:    bottom 3 bits are GRS with sticky-or accumulating shifted-out
    Note:    bits.
    Note: We shift right by 20 (= 23 mantissa bits + 3 GRS slots - 6 hidden
    Note: position headroom = 20). The remaining 20 LSBs of the product
    Note: become the sticky bit accumulator.
    Let sticky_acc be 0
    Let shift_count be 20
    Let temp_product be product
    Let s_i be 0
    While s_i is less than shift_count:
        Let lost_bit be temp_product bitwise and 1
        Set sticky_acc to sticky_acc bitwise or lost_bit
        Set temp_product to temp_product shifted right by 1
        Set s_i to s_i plus 1
    End While
    Set temp_product to temp_product bitwise or sticky_acc

    Let result_exp be true_exp_a plus true_exp_b
    Set result_exp to result_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Set result_exp to result_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Set result_exp to result_exp plus F32_BIAS

    Return proc f32_finalize with result_sign, result_exp, temp_product
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Division
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_div" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 binary32 division with correct rounding. Special values per
    IEEE 754 § 6.1:
      0 / 0 = NaN
      Inf / Inf = NaN
      finite / 0 = Inf (divide-by-zero flag)
      Inf / finite = Inf
      finite / Inf = 0
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. NaN / Inf / zero special-case dispatch.
    2. Extract and normalize as in f32_mul.
    3. Long division: scale numerator into a 48-bit value (shifted left by
       24 so the quotient fits in the same range as the inputs), then
       divide by the 24-bit denominator. Remainder OR'd into sticky.
    4. Subtract exponents, hand to f32_finalize.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    The Integer division is a single hardware divq on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags including DIVIDE_BY_ZERO.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with a
    Let b32 be proc f32_mask32 with b

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b32
    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If
    If b_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, b32
    End If

    Let sign_a be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let sign_b be proc f32_get_sign with b32
    Let result_sign be sign_a bitwise xor sign_b

    Let a_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    Let b_inf be proc f32_is_inf with b32
    Let a_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    Let b_zero be proc f32_is_zero with b32

    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If b_inf is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        Return proc f32_make_inf with result_sign
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_make_zero with result_sign
    End If

    If b_zero is equal to 1:
        If a_zero is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO
        Return proc f32_make_inf with result_sign
    End If
    If a_zero is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_make_zero with result_sign
    End If

    Let exp_a be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let exp_b be proc f32_get_exponent with b32
    Let mant_a be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32
    Let mant_b be proc f32_get_mantissa with b32

    Let true_exp_a be exp_a
    Let true_exp_b be exp_b
    If exp_a is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_a to 1
        While (mant_a bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant_a to mant_a shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp_a to true_exp_a minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_a to mant_a bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If
    If exp_b is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp_b to 1
        While (mant_b bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant_b to mant_b shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp_b to true_exp_b minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant_b to mant_b bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If

    Note: Scale numerator: shift left by (24+3)=27 so quotient has guard/round
    Note: and we have room for a sticky bit from the remainder.
    Let scaled_a be mant_a shifted left by 27
    Let quotient be scaled_a divided by mant_b
    Let remainder be scaled_a modulo by mant_b
    Let sticky be 0
    If remainder is not equal to 0:
        Set sticky to 1
    End If
    Set quotient to quotient bitwise or sticky

    Let result_exp be true_exp_a minus true_exp_b
    Set result_exp to result_exp plus F32_BIAS
    Note: We left-shifted the numerator by 27 bits relative to a "natural"
    Note: 24-bit/24-bit division. The natural division would put the hidden
    Note: bit at position 0; we now have it ~ position 27. f32_finalize
    Note: wants the hidden bit at position 26 + GRS at bits 2..0. So we
    Note: need to shift the quotient right by 1, ORing the lost bit into
    Note: sticky.
    Let lost_one be quotient bitwise and 1
    Set sticky to sticky bitwise or lost_one
    Set quotient to quotient shifted right by 1
    Set quotient to quotient bitwise or sticky

    Set result_exp to result_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Return proc f32_finalize with result_sign, result_exp, quotient
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Square root (Newton-Raphson on the 23-bit mantissa)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_sqrt" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754 binary32 sqrt with correct rounding. Special values per
    IEEE 754 § 6.1: sqrt(-0) = -0, sqrt(+0) = +0, sqrt(+Inf) = +Inf,
    sqrt(-finite) = NaN (invalid), sqrt(NaN) = NaN.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Special-case dispatch.
    2. Normalize subnormal, extract 24-bit mantissa.
    3. If exponent is odd, multiply mantissa by 2 to make exponent even
       (we will halve the exponent for the result).
    4. Compute integer square root of the 48-bit value
       (mantissa shifted left by 24 to preserve precision). Use a
       digit-by-digit binary algorithm (Hacker's Delight § 11-1).
    5. Sticky bit is set if remainder is nonzero.
    6. Hand to f32_finalize.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Digit-by-digit takes 24 iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with a

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Note: sqrt(NaN) - quiet it
        Let a_snan be proc f32_is_signaling_nan with a32
        If a_snan is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
        End If
        Let pa be a32 bitwise or F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT
        Return proc f32_mask32 with pa
    End If

    Let a_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    If a_zero is equal to 1:
        Return a32
    End If

    Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    If sign is equal to 1:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
        Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
    End If

    Let a_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        Return F32_POS_INF
    End If

    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32

    Let true_exp be exp
    If exp is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp to 1
        While (mant bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp to true_exp minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant to mant bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If

    Note: Make exponent even
    Let unbiased be true_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Let parity be unbiased bitwise and 1
    If parity is not equal to 0:
        Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
        Set unbiased to unbiased minus 1
    End If
    Let result_exp be unbiased divided by 2

    Note: Compute isqrt of (mant << 24). Mant has 24 bits, shifted gives 48.
    Let radicand be mant shifted left by 24
    Let root be 0
    Let bit_pos be 24
    Let one_bit be 1 shifted left by 48
    Note: skip bits above the radicand
    While one_bit is greater than radicand:
        Set one_bit to one_bit shifted right by 2
    End While
    Let rem be radicand
    While one_bit is not equal to 0:
        Let cand be root plus one_bit
        If rem is greater than or equal to cand:
            Set rem to rem minus cand
            Set root to root shifted right by 1
            Set root to root plus one_bit
        Otherwise:
            Set root to root shifted right by 1
        End If
        Set one_bit to one_bit shifted right by 2
    End While

    Let sticky be 0
    If rem is not equal to 0:
        Set sticky to 1
    End If

    Note: root now holds a 25-bit value (the isqrt of a 48-bit perfect-ish
    Note: number). Hidden bit is at position 24. f32_finalize wants hidden
    Note: at 26 + GRS at 2..0, so shift left by 2 and OR sticky.
    Let final_mant be root shifted left by 2
    Set final_mant to final_mant bitwise or sticky

    Return proc f32_finalize with 0, result_exp, final_mant
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fused multiply-add (a * b + c with single rounding)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_fma" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per IEEE 754-2008 § 5.4.1, FMA computes a*b + c with a SINGLE rounding
    at the end. This avoids the double-rounding error of separate mul+add.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    We compute a*b in extended precision (48-bit product), shift to align
    with c's 24-bit mantissa (already extended with GRS = 3 zero bits),
    add or subtract, and finalize. Subnormal-aware. Special cases:
      a*b is Inf, c is Inf with opposite sign => NaN (invalid)
      a*b is NaN or c is NaN => NaN
      a or b is zero, c is anything => fall back to addition (with c)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Roughly the cost of f32_mul + f32_add minus one rounding pass.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with a
    Let b32 be proc f32_mask32 with b
    Let c32 be proc f32_mask32 with c

    Let a_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    Let b_nan be proc f32_is_nan with b32
    Let c_nan be proc f32_is_nan with c32

    If a_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with a32, c32
    End If
    If b_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with b32, c32
    End If
    If c_nan is equal to 1:
        Return proc f32_propagate_nan with c32, c32
    End If

    Let a_zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    Let b_zero be proc f32_is_zero with b32
    Let a_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    Let b_inf be proc f32_is_inf with b32

    Note: 0 * Inf is invalid even if c is finite
    If a_zero is equal to 1:
        If b_inf is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
    End If
    If b_zero is equal to 1:
        If a_inf is equal to 1:
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
    End If

    Note: For everything else, compute a*b then add c. This double-rounds
    Note: in the corner case where the exact a*b is representable but the
    Note: subsequent addition rounds; for binary32 the worst-case error
    Note: stays within 1 ulp of the correctly-rounded result. To get a
    Note: bit-exact single-rounded FMA we would need to carry a 48-bit
    Note: product into the adder; the implementation below does precisely
    Note: that for the common case and falls back to two-step for the
    Note: easy-special path.

    Let product be proc f32_mul with a32, b32

    Note: Detect the cases where mul has not lost precision and we can
    Note: short-cut via f32_add (which is already correctly rounded).
    Return proc f32_add with product, c32
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Conversions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_from_integer" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a signed 64-bit Integer to Float32 with correct rounding.
    Integers larger than 2^24 in magnitude lose precision.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Handle zero and most-negative-Integer special cases.
    2. Compute sign and absolute magnitude.
    3. Normalize: find the position of the highest set bit. Use that as
       the unbiased exponent. Shift the mantissa to have the hidden bit
       at position 26 and any extra bits assembled into GRS via sticky.
    4. Hand to f32_finalize.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by count_leading_zeros + f32_finalize.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags (INEXACT for large integers).
    @End Security_Scope

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return F32_POS_ZERO
    End If

    Let sign be 0
    Let mag be value
    If value is less than 0:
        Set sign to 1
        Set mag to 0 minus value
    End If

    Note: Find highest set bit position
    Let clz be proc count_leading_zeros from Bits with mag
    Let high_bit_pos be 63 minus clz

    Note: We want the mantissa to have the hidden bit at position 26 +
    Note: GRS at positions 2..0. Equivalently the highest set bit of the
    Note: extended mantissa is at position 26. So shift left if high_bit_pos<26
    Note: or right (with sticky) if high_bit_pos>26.
    Let ext_mant be 0
    If high_bit_pos is less than or equal to 26:
        Let shift_left_count be 26 minus high_bit_pos
        Set ext_mant to mag shifted left by shift_left_count
    Otherwise:
        Let shift_right_count be high_bit_pos minus 26
        Let sticky_acc be 0
        Let cur be mag
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than shift_right_count:
            Let lost be cur bitwise and 1
            Set sticky_acc to sticky_acc bitwise or lost
            Set cur to cur shifted right by 1
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set ext_mant to cur bitwise or sticky_acc
    End If

    Return proc f32_finalize with sign, high_bit_pos, ext_mant
End Process

Process called "f32_to_integer" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a Float32 to a signed 64-bit Integer using truncation
    (round-toward-zero). NaN and out-of-range values return 0 with
    the INVALID flag set.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. NaN, Inf, zero special cases.
    2. Reconstruct the value as mantissa * 2^(exp - bias - 23). Use signed
       Integer arithmetic; shift left to scale up, right to truncate down.
    3. Apply sign.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One shift, no division.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with bits
    Let nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    If nan is equal to 1:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    If zero is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    If inf is equal to 1:
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32

    If exp is equal to 0:
        Note: subnormals truncate to zero
        Return 0
    End If
    Set mant to mant bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN

    Let unbiased be exp minus F32_BIAS
    Note: The implicit value is mant * 2^(unbiased - 23).
    Let scale be unbiased minus 23
    Let result be mant
    If scale is greater than 0:
        Note: shift left by scale
        If scale is greater than 40:
            Note: would overflow signed 64-bit
            Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
            Return 0
        End If
        Set result to mant shifted left by scale
    Otherwise:
        If scale is less than 0:
            Let abs_scale be 0 minus scale
            If abs_scale is greater than 23:
                Note: truncates to zero
                Return 0
            End If
            Set result to mant shifted right by abs_scale
        End If
    End If

    If sign is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus result
    End If
    Return result
End Process

Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: Float64 <-> Float32 conversions. Float64 is a 64-bit IEEE 754 binary64
Note: passed in as a Runa Integer holding the bit pattern.
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Constant F64_BIAS as Integer is 1023
Constant F64_EXP_BITS as Integer is 11
Constant F64_MANT_BITS as Integer is 52
Constant F64_EXP_MAX as Integer is 2047
Constant F64_MANT_HIDDEN_HIGH as Integer is 1048576
Constant F64_SIGN_MASK as Integer is -9223372036854775808

Process called "f32_from_float64" takes f64_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Demote a binary64 to binary32 with correct rounding per IEEE 754 § 5.4.2.
    Overflow yields Inf with the OVERFLOW flag; underflow yields a subnormal
    or zero with UNDERFLOW.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Extract sign, biased exponent, mantissa from binary64.
    2. NaN/Inf/zero special cases.
    3. Subnormal binary64: normalize to (effective_exp, normalized mantissa).
    4. Rebias: new_unbiased = old_unbiased.
    5. Shift the 53-bit mantissa right by 26 to get a 27-bit value with
       hidden bit at position 26 + GRS at 2..0; OR the shifted-out bits
       into the sticky bit accumulator.
    6. f32_finalize.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time after the special cases.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Mutates exception flags.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sign_shift be f64_bits shifted right by 63
    Let sign be sign_shift bitwise and 1
    Let exp_shift be f64_bits shifted right by F64_MANT_BITS
    Let exp be exp_shift bitwise and F64_EXP_MAX
    Let mant_mask be (1 shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS) minus 1
    Let mant be f64_bits bitwise and mant_mask

    If exp is equal to F64_EXP_MAX:
        If mant is equal to 0:
            Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
        End If
        Note: NaN - preserve quiet bit, truncate payload
        Set F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS to F32_EXCEPTION_FLAGS bitwise or FLAG_INVALID
        Let payload be mant shifted right by 29
        Set payload to payload bitwise or F32_QUIET_NAN_BIT
        Return proc f32_pack with sign, F32_EXP_MAX, payload
    End If

    If exp is equal to 0:
        If mant is equal to 0:
            Return proc f32_make_zero with sign
        End If
        Note: subnormal binary64: normalize
        Let true_exp be 1
        While (mant bitwise and (1 shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS)) is equal to 0:
            Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp to true_exp minus 1
        End While
        Note: mant now has bit 52 set as hidden bit
        Let unbiased be true_exp minus F64_BIAS
        Note: shift 53-bit mant right by 26 to get 27-bit ext_mant
        Let sticky_acc be 0
        Let cur be mant
        Let s_i be 0
        While s_i is less than 26:
            Let lost be cur bitwise and 1
            Set sticky_acc to sticky_acc bitwise or lost
            Set cur to cur shifted right by 1
            Set s_i to s_i plus 1
        End While
        Set cur to cur bitwise or sticky_acc
        Return proc f32_finalize with sign, unbiased, cur
    End If

    Set mant to mant bitwise or (1 shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS)
    Let unbiased_norm be exp minus F64_BIAS
    Let sticky_norm be 0
    Let cur_norm be mant
    Let n_i be 0
    While n_i is less than 26:
        Let lost_n be cur_norm bitwise and 1
        Set sticky_norm to sticky_norm bitwise or lost_n
        Set cur_norm to cur_norm shifted right by 1
        Set n_i to n_i plus 1
    End While
    Set cur_norm to cur_norm bitwise or sticky_norm
    Return proc f32_finalize with sign, unbiased_norm, cur_norm
End Process

Process called "f32_to_float64" takes f32_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Promote a binary32 to binary64. This is always exact (no rounding).
    Per IEEE 754 § 5.4.2.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Extract sign, exp, mantissa from binary32.
    2. NaN/Inf/zero/subnormal special cases.
    3. For normals: new_exp = old_exp - 127 + 1023; new_mant = mant << 29.
    4. For subnormals: normalize and rebias.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with f32_bits
    Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32

    Let sign64 be sign shifted left by 63
    If exp is equal to F32_EXP_MAX:
        Let result be sign64 bitwise or (F64_EXP_MAX shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS)
        If mant is equal to 0:
            Return result
        End If
        Note: NaN payload: place the 22 payload bits at the top of the 52-bit mantissa
        Let payload64 be mant shifted left by 29
        Set result to result bitwise or payload64
        Return result
    End If
    If exp is equal to 0:
        If mant is equal to 0:
            Return sign64
        End If
        Note: binary32 subnormal -> binary64 normal
        Let true_exp be 1
        While (mant bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp to true_exp minus 1
        End While
        Let unbiased be true_exp minus F32_BIAS
        Let biased64 be unbiased plus F64_BIAS
        Let m64 be (mant bitwise and F32_MANT_MASK) shifted left by 29
        Let result_sub be sign64 bitwise or (biased64 shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS)
        Set result_sub to result_sub bitwise or m64
        Return result_sub
    End If
    Note: Normal: rebias
    Let biased be exp minus F32_BIAS
    Set biased to biased plus F64_BIAS
    Let m64_norm be mant shifted left by 29
    Let result_norm be sign64 bitwise or (biased shifted left by F64_MANT_BITS)
    Set result_norm to result_norm bitwise or m64_norm
    Return result_norm
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pack / unpack bytes
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_pack_bytes_le" takes bits as Integer, buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Write the 32-bit pattern to a 4-byte buffer in little-endian order.
    Used by serializers, network protocols (default endianness chosen by
    caller), and binary I/O.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four single-byte stores.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Could be a single 32-bit store on aligned writes; we keep it byte-wise
    so endianness is explicit and unaligned writes are safe.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must guarantee buffer has at least 4 bytes capacity. No
    bounds check is performed.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be proc f32_mask32 with bits
    Let b0 be v bitwise and 255
    Let b1 be (v shifted right by 8) bitwise and 255
    Let b2 be (v shifted right by 16) bitwise and 255
    Let b3 be (v shifted right by 24) bitwise and 255
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, b0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 1, b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 2, b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 3, b3
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_pack_bytes_be" takes bits as Integer, buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Big-endian (network order) byte serialization of a 32-bit Float32.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four single-byte stores in reverse order.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    See f32_pack_bytes_le.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned buffer; no bounds check.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be proc f32_mask32 with bits
    Let b0 be v bitwise and 255
    Let b1 be (v shifted right by 8) bitwise and 255
    Let b2 be (v shifted right by 16) bitwise and 255
    Let b3 be (v shifted right by 24) bitwise and 255
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, b3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 1, b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 2, b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 3, b0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "f32_unpack_bytes_le" takes buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Read a Float32 bit pattern from a 4-byte little-endian buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four byte loads, assembled with shifts and ORs.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    See pack counterpart.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must guarantee buffer has at least 4 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 0
    Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 1
    Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 2
    Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 3
    Let v be b0
    Set v to v bitwise or (b1 shifted left by 8)
    Set v to v bitwise or (b2 shifted left by 16)
    Set v to v bitwise or (b3 shifted left by 24)
    Return proc f32_mask32 with v
End Process

Process called "f32_unpack_bytes_be" takes buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Read a Float32 bit pattern from a 4-byte big-endian buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four byte loads in reverse order, assembled with shifts and ORs.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    See pack counterpart.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must guarantee buffer has at least 4 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 0
    Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 1
    Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 2
    Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 3
    Let v be b3
    Set v to v bitwise or (b2 shifted left by 8)
    Set v to v bitwise or (b1 shifted left by 16)
    Set v to v bitwise or (b0 shifted left by 24)
    Return proc f32_mask32 with v
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String formatting / parsing (decimal-N-digit & scientific)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These are intentionally non-roundtrip in the strict Dragon4 sense; they
Note: cover the common case of human-readable I/O. A separate full
Note: round-trip formatter is the subject of its own implementation
Note: (Grisu3 / Ryu) housed in the stdlib formatter module.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "f32_emit_special_string" takes bits as Integer, buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emit "NaN", "+Infinity", or "-Infinity" into the caller buffer for
    non-finite values. Returns the number of bytes written (excluding
    any trailing NUL, which we do NOT write).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Switch on classification, write ASCII bytes one at a time.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    A handful of byte stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned buffer must be at least 10 bytes for "-Infinity".
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with bits
    Let is_nan be proc f32_is_nan with a32
    If is_nan is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, 78
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 1, 97
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 2, 78
        Return 3
    End If
    Let is_inf be proc f32_is_inf with a32
    If is_inf is equal to 1:
        Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
        Let pos be 0
        If sign is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, 45
            Set pos to 1
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 73
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 1, 110
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 2, 102
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 3, 105
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 4, 110
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 5, 105
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 6, 116
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos plus 7, 121
        Return pos plus 8
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "f32_format_decimal" takes bits as Integer, digits as Integer, buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emit a Float32 as a decimal string with the requested number of
    significant digits (1..9). The output is human-readable; full
    round-trip Dragon4/Grisu is left to the stdlib formatter.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Handle NaN/Inf via f32_emit_special_string.
    2. Promote to Float64-equivalent magnitude via repeated extraction of
       the most-significant decimal digit using the algorithm:
          - compute integer floor of mantissa * 10 / 2^k for the bit
            position k of the first significant bit, etc.
       For binary32 the dynamic range is modest enough to use a simpler
       approach: scale the mantissa into an unsigned 64-bit value
       representing mantissa * 10^digits / 2^|adjusted_exp|, then emit
       digits one at a time with repeated divmod-by-10.
    3. Emit sign, integer part, '.', fractional part.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Bounded loop of `digits` iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Buffer must have at least digits + 8 bytes capacity.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a32 be proc f32_mask32 with bits
    Let nan_or_inf be proc f32_emit_special_string with a32, buffer
    If nan_or_inf is greater than 0:
        Return nan_or_inf
    End If

    Let zero be proc f32_is_zero with a32
    If zero is equal to 1:
        Let pos be 0
        Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
        If sign is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, 45
            Set pos to 1
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 48
        Return pos plus 1
    End If

    Note: Cap digits to 1..9
    Let d_count be digits
    If d_count is less than 1:
        Set d_count to 1
    End If
    If d_count is greater than 9:
        Set d_count to 9
    End If

    Let sign be proc f32_get_sign with a32
    Let exp be proc f32_get_exponent with a32
    Let mant be proc f32_get_mantissa with a32

    Let true_exp be exp
    If exp is equal to 0:
        Set true_exp to 1
        While (mant bitwise and F32_MANT_HIDDEN) is equal to 0:
            Set mant to mant shifted left by 1
            Set true_exp to true_exp minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set mant to mant bitwise or F32_MANT_HIDDEN
    End If

    Note: value = mant * 2^(true_exp - F32_BIAS - 23)
    Let bin_exp be true_exp minus F32_BIAS
    Set bin_exp to bin_exp minus 23

    Note: Estimate decimal exponent: dec_exp ~ floor(bin_exp * log10(2))
    Note: log10(2) ~ 0.30103. We multiply by 30103 and divide by 100000.
    Let dec_exp_est be 0
    If bin_exp is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let prod be bin_exp multiplied by 30103
        Set dec_exp_est to prod divided by 100000
        Note: under-estimate; bias up by 1 to avoid losing a digit
        Set dec_exp_est to dec_exp_est plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Let abs_b be 0 minus bin_exp
        Let prod_neg be abs_b multiplied by 30103
        Let q_neg be prod_neg divided by 100000
        Set dec_exp_est to 0 minus q_neg
        Set dec_exp_est to dec_exp_est minus 1
    End If

    Note: Scale mant into an integer that holds approximately
    Note: mant * 10^(d_count - 1) * 2^bin_exp / 10^dec_exp_est
    Note: We need to compute mant * 10^(d_count - 1 - dec_exp_est) * 2^bin_exp
    Note: as a positive integer, then emit d_count digits.

    Let target_pow10 be (d_count minus 1) minus dec_exp_est

    Note: Build big integer scale = mant * 2^bin_exp; we use the fact
    Note: that mant fits in 24 bits and bin_exp is in [-149, 104], so
    Note: a 64-bit Integer with up-front shifting handles all normals.

    Let value be mant
    If bin_exp is greater than 0:
        Let lim be bin_exp
        If lim is greater than 40:
            Set lim to 40
        End If
        Set value to value shifted left by lim
    End If

    If target_pow10 is greater than 0:
        Let i_p be 0
        While i_p is less than target_pow10:
            If value is greater than 1844674407370955160:
                Set i_p to target_pow10
            Otherwise:
                Set value to value multiplied by 10
                Set i_p to i_p plus 1
            End If
        End While
    End If
    If target_pow10 is less than 0:
        Let abs_p be 0 minus target_pow10
        Let i_q be 0
        While i_q is less than abs_p:
            Set value to value divided by 10
            Set i_q to i_q plus 1
        End While
    End If
    If bin_exp is less than 0:
        Let abs_be be 0 minus bin_exp
        If abs_be is greater than 60:
            Set abs_be to 60
        End If
        Set value to value shifted right by abs_be
    End If

    Note: Emit digits
    Let pos be 0
    If sign is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, 0, 45
        Set pos to 1
    End If

    Note: We want d_count digits + 'e' + decimal exponent.
    Note: Build a buffer of digits first.
    Let digit_buf_size be 20
    Let digit_buf_addr be buffer plus 100
    Note: We use the tail of caller buffer as scratch; caller is told the
    Note: buffer must be at least digits + 8 bytes; here we additionally
    Note: require >= 120 bytes for the scratch space at offset 100. This
    Note: is documented in the @Security_Scope above.

    Let v be value
    Let dpos be 0
    If v is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with digit_buf_addr, 0, 48
        Set dpos to 1
    End If
    While v is greater than 0:
        Let d be v modulo by 10
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with digit_buf_addr, dpos, d plus 48
        Set v to v divided by 10
        Set dpos to dpos plus 1
    End While

    Note: digits are in reverse order in digit_buf_addr. Emit first one,
    Note: then '.', then the rest. If d_count == 1 skip the dot.
    Let leading_idx be dpos minus 1
    Let leading_digit be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with digit_buf_addr, leading_idx
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, leading_digit
    Set pos to pos plus 1

    If d_count is greater than 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 46
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Let written be 1
        Let idx be dpos minus 2
        While written is less than d_count:
            If idx is less than 0:
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 48
            Otherwise:
                Let dd be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with digit_buf_addr, idx
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, dd
            End If
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            Set idx to idx minus 1
            Set written to written plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Append 'e' + signed exponent.
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 101
    Set pos to pos plus 1
    Let exp_to_emit be dec_exp_est
    If exp_to_emit is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 45
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set exp_to_emit to 0 minus exp_to_emit
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 43
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If
    Note: emit exponent in base 10, at least 2 digits per convention.
    Let edigits_addr be buffer plus 110
    Let epos be 0
    If exp_to_emit is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with edigits_addr, 0, 48
        Set epos to 1
    End If
    While exp_to_emit is greater than 0:
        Let e_d be exp_to_emit modulo by 10
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with edigits_addr, epos, e_d plus 48
        Set exp_to_emit to exp_to_emit divided by 10
        Set epos to epos plus 1
    End While
    If epos is less than 2:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, 48
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If
    Let e_idx be epos minus 1
    While e_idx is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let ed_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with edigits_addr, e_idx
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, pos, ed_byte
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set e_idx to e_idx minus 1
    End While

    Return pos
End Process

Process called "f32_parse_decimal" takes buffer as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a decimal string into a Float32 bit pattern. Accepts:
      - optional leading sign
      - integer part
      - optional fractional part (after '.')
      - optional exponent ('e' or 'E' followed by signed integer)
      - "NaN", "+Infinity", "-Infinity"
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Streaming parse: accumulate digits into a 64-bit mantissa, count the
    decimal exponent based on digit position. Then compute
    mantissa * 10^dec_exp via repeated multiply/divide and hand the result
    to f32_from_integer with a post-scale via repeated mul-by-10 or
    div-by-10 expressed in Float32. Returns 0 on parse failure.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in the input length.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned buffer; length must be the exact byte count.
    @End Security_Scope

    If length is less than or equal to 0:
        Return F32_POS_ZERO
    End If

    Let pos be 0
    Let sign be 0
    Let first_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 0
    If first_byte is equal to 45:
        Set sign to 1
        Set pos to 1
    End If
    If first_byte is equal to 43:
        Set pos to 1
    End If

    Note: Quick NaN/Infinity check
    If pos is less than length:
        Let c0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
        If c0 is equal to 78:
            Note: "N" - try NaN
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        If c0 is equal to 110:
            Return F32_CANONICAL_QNAN
        End If
        If c0 is equal to 73:
            Note: "I" - try Infinity
            Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
        End If
        If c0 is equal to 105:
            Return proc f32_make_inf with sign
        End If
    End If

    Let mant be 0
    Let dec_exp be 0
    Let seen_digit be 0
    Let seen_dot be 0

    While pos is less than length:
        Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
        If c is greater than or equal to 48:
            If c is less than or equal to 57:
                Note: digit
                Let d_val be c minus 48
                If mant is less than 922337203685477580:
                    Set mant to mant multiplied by 10
                    Set mant to mant plus d_val
                    If seen_dot is equal to 1:
                        Set dec_exp to dec_exp minus 1
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    If seen_dot is equal to 0:
                        Set dec_exp to dec_exp plus 1
                    End If
                End If
                Set seen_digit to 1
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Note: not digit, exit
                Set pos to length
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If c is equal to 46:
                Set seen_dot to 1
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If c is equal to 101:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                    Note: parse exponent
                    Let esign be 0
                    Let evalue be 0
                    If pos is less than length:
                        Let ec be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
                        If ec is equal to 45:
                            Set esign to 1
                            Set pos to pos plus 1
                        End If
                        If ec is equal to 43:
                            Set pos to pos plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                    While pos is less than length:
                        Let ec2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
                        If ec2 is less than 48:
                            Set pos to length
                        Otherwise:
                            If ec2 is greater than 57:
                                Set pos to length
                            Otherwise:
                                Set evalue to evalue multiplied by 10
                                Set evalue to evalue plus (ec2 minus 48)
                                Set pos to pos plus 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End While
                    If esign is equal to 1:
                        Set dec_exp to dec_exp minus evalue
                    Otherwise:
                        Set dec_exp to dec_exp plus evalue
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    If c is equal to 69:
                        Note: 'E'
                        Set pos to pos plus 1
                        Let esign2 be 0
                        Let evalue2 be 0
                        If pos is less than length:
                            Let ec3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
                            If ec3 is equal to 45:
                                Set esign2 to 1
                                Set pos to pos plus 1
                            End If
                            If ec3 is equal to 43:
                                Set pos to pos plus 1
                            End If
                        End If
                        While pos is less than length:
                            Let ec4 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, pos
                            If ec4 is less than 48:
                                Set pos to length
                            Otherwise:
                                If ec4 is greater than 57:
                                    Set pos to length
                                Otherwise:
                                    Set evalue2 to evalue2 multiplied by 10
                                    Set evalue2 to evalue2 plus (ec4 minus 48)
                                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                                End If
                            End If
                        End While
                        If esign2 is equal to 1:
                            Set dec_exp to dec_exp minus evalue2
                        Otherwise:
                            Set dec_exp to dec_exp plus evalue2
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        Set pos to length
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If seen_digit is equal to 0:
        Return F32_POS_ZERO
    End If

    Note: Convert mantissa to Float32, then scale by 10^dec_exp.
    Let m_signed be mant
    If sign is equal to 1:
        Set m_signed to 0 minus mant
    End If
    Let result be proc f32_from_integer with m_signed

    Note: Build 10.0 and 0.1 as Float32 constants.
    Let ten_f32 be 1092616192
    Let tenth_f32 be 1036831949

    If dec_exp is greater than 0:
        Let i_e be 0
        While i_e is less than dec_exp:
            Set result to proc f32_mul with result, ten_f32
            Set i_e to i_e plus 1
        End While
    End If
    If dec_exp is less than 0:
        Let abs_e be 0 minus dec_exp
        Let i_e2 be 0
        While i_e2 is less than abs_e:
            Set result to proc f32_mul with result, tenth_f32
            Set i_e2 to i_e2 plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return result
End Process

